title: 9. Exocrine Glands may be Unicellular: Goblet Cells

vectorData.altText: H1   Exocrine Glands may be Unicellular: Goblet Cells

goblet cells are unicellular, mucous-secreting, exocrine glands interspersed amongst epithelial cells
secrete mucous across their apical aspect onto the exposed surface of an epithelial sheet to protect the cells of the covering epithelia
e.g. respiratory epithelium, where it traps inhaled particles; the mucous (and particles) are cleared from the respiratory tract
e.g. digestive tract     , where it lubricates surfaces to ease passage of contents
Goblet Cells are Shaped like a Water Goblet
